data: {"type": "text-delta", "id": "73906d3f-2ce2-424b-b265-f95f8d965976", "delta": "### PostgreSQL Replication Lag Mini-Runbook\n\n1. **Check Replication Status**: Run `SELECT client_addr, state, sent_lsn, write_lsn, flush_lsn, replay_lsn, sync_state FROM pg_stat_replication;` on the primary to identify active replicas and their current state.\n2. **Calculate Lag in Bytes**: Execute `SELECT pg_wal_lsn_diff(pg_current_wal_lsn(), replay_lsn) AS lag_bytes FROM pg_stat_replication;` to quantify the replication lag in bytes for each replica.\n3. **Calculate Lag in Time**: Run `SELECT now() - pg_last_xact_replay_timestamp() AS lag_time FROM pg_stat_replication;` to determine the time delay between the primary and each replica.\n4. **Check Replica Health**: Verify the replica's ability to accept connections and check for any errors in the PostgreSQL logs (`/var/log/postgresql/postgresql-*.log` or `pg_log` directory) on the replica server.\n5. **Review Long-Running Queries**: On the primary, execute `SELECT pid, usename, state, query, query_start, age(now(), query_start) AS duration FROM pg_stat_activity WHERE state != 'idle' ORDER BY duration DESC LIMIT 10;` to identify queries that might be causing replication delays."}

